Alice, you are correct in pointing out that the original answer counts ordered pairs $(A, B)$ rather than unordered partitions $\{A, B\}$. For even $n = 2k$, the formula should indeed be $\frac{1}{2}\binom{n}{n/2}$ to account for the fact that each partition is counted twice. Similarly, for odd $n = 2k+1$, the configurations '$k$ and $k+1$' and '$k+1$ and $k$' represent the same unordered partition, so the factor of 2 is unnecessary. Therefore, the correct formula for $P(n)$ is:

$$
P(n) = 
\begin{cases} 
\frac{1}{2}\binom{n}{n/2}, & \text{if } n \text{ is even} \\
\binom{n}{(n-1)/2}, & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}
\end{cases}
$$

Using this corrected formula, $P(10) = \frac{1}{2}\binom{10}{5} = 126$. Thank you for the critique, and I agree with your assessment.
